# Types of Reinforcement Learning

## Model-Based RL

Agent learns a model of the environment.

---

## Model-Free RL

Agent learns directly through experience.

Q-Learning belongs to this category.

---

# What is Q-Learning?

Q-Learning is one of the most popular Reinforcement Learning algorithms.

It helps an agent learn the best action to take in every state.

The algorithm stores learned knowledge in a structure called a Q-Table.

---

# Meaning of Q

Q stands for:

Quality

It represents how good a particular action is in a particular state.

---

# Q-Table

The Q-Table stores:

State

↓

Action

↓

Expected Future Reward

---

# Example Q-Table

| State | Up | Down | Left | Right |
| ----- | -- | ---- | ---- | ----- |
| S0    | 10 | 15   | 8    | 20    |
| S1    | 5  | 25   | 10   | 18    |

The agent selects actions with higher Q-values.

---

# Q-Learning Workflow

Initialize Q-Table

↓

Choose Action

↓

Perform Action

↓

Receive Reward

↓

Update Q-Value

↓

Repeat

↓

Learn Optimal Policy

---

# Q-Learning Formula

The Q-value is updated using:

Q(s,a) = Q(s,a) + α[r + γ max(Q') − Q(s,a)]

Where:

* Q(s,a) = Current Q-value
* α = Learning Rate
* r = Reward
* γ = Discount Factor
* max(Q') = Best Future Reward

---

# Understanding Learning Rate (α)

Controls how quickly the agent learns.

Low Value:

Slow learning

High Value:

Fast learning

---

# Understanding Discount Factor (γ)

Controls importance of future rewards.

γ = 0

Agent only cares about immediate rewards.

γ close to 1

Agent values future rewards.

---

# Exploration vs Exploitation

One of the most important RL concepts.

---

## Exploration

Trying new actions.

Example:

Testing a new route in the maze.

---

## Exploitation

Using known best actions.

Example:

Following the already learned shortest path.

---

# Why Exploration is Important

Without exploration:

The agent may never discover better solutions.

---

# Advantages of Q-Learning

* Simple to understand
* Model-free algorithm
* Learns optimal actions
* Effective for small environments

---

# Limitations of Q-Learning

* Q-Table becomes huge for large problems
* Slow for complex environments
* Not suitable for large state spaces

